shared_text:
Parent Participation ~ San Luis Coastal
September 1 at 9:04 AM ·

Introducing FREE Online Evening Discussion Classes just for Parents! Gain parenting knowledge and form connections with other families from the comfort and safety of your own home. Join a class specific to your child’s age (infants, young toddlers, older toddlers, preschoolers) lead by Parent Participation teachers for one hour in the evening, once a week. Teachers provide current information about parenting topics relevant to your child, and then facilitate a discussion so that everyone can learn from each other and share experiences. All classes will include parenting resources, ideas for activities to keep little ones engaged at home, and personal support and connection from your teacher.
Classes are held weekly and require internet connection and the Zoom application.

September 14th - November 20th
Enroll today at https://slcusd.asapconnected.com/#CourseGroupID=23145

post_text: Join a free online parenting class this summer! Register through the Adult School SLOadultschool.org
shared_text:
Parent Participation ~ San Luis Coastal
June 15 at 11:12 AM ·

FREE online Love&Logic parenting class❣️❤️Love allows children to grow through their mistakes. Logic allows them to live with the consequences of their choices.
This unique online class format will be facilitated via Zoom and comprised of lectures, individual/partner activity, discussions, and question and answer sessions. Special topics of interest include the impact of discipline during COVID-19, social/racial justice, and healthy relationships between parents and children.
THIS FREE CLASS MEETS ONLINE FOR FIVE SESSIONS: Wednesdays, 7:00-9:00 pm, July 8th - Aug. 5th
❤️Students MUST pre-enroll❣️Visit: https://slcusd.asapconnected.com/#CourseID=224952
Please share- although this is locally facilitated, anyone anywhere can enroll!❤️

post_text: Adult School Collaborating with SLOHS is a picnic - Tuesday morning Jed Bruington's Industrial Technology class delivered a picnic table to the Parent Participation Program at the Adult School. The octagonal picnic table used for outdoor parent discussions had deteriorated to the point of being unsafe. SLOHS to the rescue! They came to pick up the table and took it to the shop. They completely redesigned it. It is bigger, sturdier, made of high quality wood, sealed to endure the sprinkler system, and it has removable benches to allow handicap access on two sides. It is a beautiful addition to the new Adult School playground!

Julie has taught Parenting the Toddler classes at Parent Participation for over 20 years! She is being honored for the 9th Children's Bill of Right "May we each make and keep healthy relationships with friends."
shared_text:
First 5 SLO County is with San Luis Obispo County Office of Education and Parent Participation ~ San Luis Coastal.
September 1, 2017 at 7:57 AM ·

What a gem we have in Julie here on the Central Coast! A community connector-- empowering parents with valuable tools and fostering life-long friendships among them. This September, we invite you to help us celebrate this very special lady who embodies the ideals of our Children's Bill of Rights for SLO County. Hit play, and hear all the reasons why Julie Martin is a true Hands-on Hero! You'll also find her featured in this month's SLO Journal Plus! And visit our website to learn more about the other Heroes working tirelessly on behalf of our youngest citizens.

San Luis Coastal USD will be hosting the 4th Annual Coastal Family Resource Fair, for children and families. The event will take place February 24, 2017 from 4-6pm at Los Osos Middle School. Entry is free of charge.

The resource fair will be offering access to a variety of FREE community, non-profit and government support services. Highlights include: Community Health Center (CHC) dental screenings and varnishes for children as well as FREE flu shots for children and adults; SLO County Food Bank will distribute healthy food boxes for every family; FREE government cell phones to qualified individuals; FREE clothing for children; FREE child ID kits; FREE taco dinner sponsored by The Link; Drug and Alcohol's Friday Night Live will also provide FREE games and much more!!!

post_text:
Due to stormy weather resulting in a loss of power and fallen trees, classes at Morro Bay High School will be canceled for the remainder of the day. All of our students are safe in their classrooms awaiting dismissal.

A message was sent to all parents of students at Morro Bay High School notifying them of the dismissal procedure. Bus riders will be loading buses and traveling home. Student drivers will be escorted to their cars by an adult and released to drive home starting at noon.

All other students need to be picked up by a parent at the west entrance bus circle. They are asked to communicate with their student via cell phone, if able, when they arrive. Staff is on site to assist parents in the parking lot if they are unable to notify students by cell.

District staff is on site and working in cooperation with the Morro Bay Fire and Police Departments to coordinate the dismissal and ensure the safety of our students.

San Luis Obispo FFA is at Cal Poly Dairy.
December 11, 2016 at 5:03 PM · San Luis Obispo, CA ·

Last Friday 30 students in our Animal Science class were able to take over the 4:30AM milking shift at the Cal Poly Dairy! They milked cows, bottle fed calves and moved hay. They also got to feed newborns their first bottles. Thank you so much to Rich Silacci and the Cal Poly Dairy Unit for providing these incredible experiential learning opportunities for our students! San Luis Coastal Unified School District (SLCUSD)

San Luis Coastal to hold forums on Diablo Canyon closure

post_text:
Public Forums Set to Discuss Impact of Diablo Canyon Closure on Schools

There will be a public forum tonight at Laguna Middle School, 11050 Los Osos Valley Road, San Luis Obispo, from 6 to 8 p.m. to discuss the impact the proposed closure of the Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant will have on our schools. An email with more information was sent to all district families. Please attend to learn about this important issue and to offer your comments. Spanish translation will be available.

Esta noche habrá un foro público en Laguna Middle School, San Luis Obispo, de los seis hasta las ocho de la noche para discutir el impacto de la propuesta de cierre de Diablo Canyon tendrá en nuestras escuelas. Un correo electrónico con más información se envió a todas las familias. Por favor asistir para aprender acerca de este importante tema y ofrecer sus comentarios. Traducción en español estará disponible.

post_text: Women in Education: Anna Bates Since 2002, Anna Bates has served as a teacher in the Agriculture Education and FFA Department of San Luis Obispo High School, where 75 percent of her students are female. She teaches a full load of classes in the agricultural department, ranging from leadership to veterinary science to integrated science, and also advises the FFA Chapter officers. In addition, she is known for going on home visits to meet the families of her freshman students in order to involve them in the activities of the agriculture department. She has conducted more than 900 home visits in the past 10 years. Bates has coached and mentored many individuals and teams in FFA competitions, some at the state and national level. In addition, the Cal Poly graduate is currently obtaining a PhD in Agriculture Education through Texas A & M and Texas Tech and in 2015, was awarded the Outstanding Distance Doctoral Student in her program. “She is an ideal role model for all women lucky enough to know her,” said her nominator Marissa Greenberg. This special award has not been given since 2010.
